      "side": 1,
      "message": "You are right that the average bitrate of screen content is lower (static, low entropy): the encoder undershoots the budget massively while nothing moves. What these factors raise is the rate-control cap, which only matters on transients (scroll, window switch, page change): with the camera-sized cap, small text after a transition smears and takes a long time to become legible at 4:2:0. Camera video spends close to its budget continuously, screen capture is bursty: high peak on change, near-zero average. So the higher cap improves transition legibility without raising the average much, and RTCP adaptation still brings it down when the link cannot sustain it. Happy to drop it if you prefer to handle this differently (e.g. tuning the encoder for screen content instead).",
      "parentUuid": "941fce98_df946541",
      "revId": "dd48d196cc0c0f0601a0ff45c4e8a01bbc2221c0",
      "serverId": "1e26b4c1-6b8c-47ff-9df7-501b633d3b5a"
    },
